metadata.description:
Paper Cut is a p5.js layered collage composition of Truchet patterns on textured paper.

metadata.name: Acequia #21
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Asterium #125
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: pointillism in lines  #8
metadata.description:
This painting is drawn in pointillism style.
which includes 14 layers.
The first 10 layers contain pointillism drawings and the 11th layer is the patterns of each line.
In the 12th layer, there are 30 covers made of different geometric shapes and brushes.
And noise and frames are used in the last two layers.

metadata.name: STRUCTURES #166
metadata.description:
STRUCTURES

What color do things look when you're happy?

First of all I want to dedicate this collection to all the people who paint their emotions with color, who through a chromatic range, are capable of feeling a universe of sensations most of the time inexplicable.....

 I am fascinated by how generative art creates a perfect symbiosis between art and technology, allowing through a set of algorithmic rules to give rise to compositions where shapes and colors coexist in balance, harmonized with each other that give rise to new creations.

This collection is designed to be self-contained and limited, recreating the view from different angles and phases of the day that can lead to disparate interpretations of a piece.

My work as a visual artist explores elements such as randomness and chance of linear formations and geometric gradients that broaden the spectrum to increasingly new concepts that I definitely want to explore.

I continually wonder what the geometric patterns that will emerge from my sensibility will be like and will give rise to new collections like this one, which is why I continue to investigate techniques and shapes while having fun.

"A painting is not the image of an experience, but it is the experience." Mark Rothk

metadata.name: overloaded #403
metadata.description: Overloaded attempts to be a system to explore time perception, through non-representative images, while still representing pixels as upscaled forms. It plays with permanence and non-permanence.

metadata.name: AI Humans #89
metadata.description:
AI Humans

The ability to integrate the use of AI into my work in some capacity is something that has been circling around my head for quite some time.

The first exploration is AI Humans; for this collection, I used Stable Diffusion to create more than 200 different faces, with different traits, and different styles.  Then those results were curated by a face recognition algorithm with some changed arguments in order to create some dystopian results.

The final countdown was 50 faces, then each face was separated into three layers

Top (cranium)
Features (eyes, nose, accessories)
Upper body (Neck & chin)

Once the layers were done, I ran the first generative test to discard possible errors, mostly layer positioning. Once these errors were corrected I ran a second and final version with amazing results.

Usually, the naming of the layers is referred to as the visual description of the trait, but in this case, I wanted to be something less human and more machine. For that matter, the layers are named with random numbers assigned by an algorithm. In the end, we all are just random numbers.

Some matches are not perfect and that is the idea. AI is not perfect (yet), and humans are not perfect either, but the results are really intriguing, the mix of features and styles is what makes our imagination fly. 

Licensing
Each AI Human is CC0, so feel free to use it as you see fit

Made with love, AI & pj5s

By CodeNFT (Clementine Novak)
September 2022

metadata.name: Klyft #560
metadata.description:
“Klyft” is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft’s expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

· URL parameters ·

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> — See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> — See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> — View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true — Save the piece as an image. 

record=true — Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‘Stokkendahl Dalgas’ color scheme:

color=14&record=true

· Interactions ·

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

· Accessibility ·

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS’ VoiceOver, and uses p5.js’ describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don’t hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

· Credits and license ·

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: gnarly tree #20
metadata.description: Hello! I'm a software developer and plant lover. I have always had a fascination for generative algorithms, fractals, and artificial life. This is my first generative NFT - a gnarly old tree. Source code was written in Scala.js with use of Three.js and ZIO. The algorithm is heavily inspired by l-systems (Lindenmayer systems), but has my own unique quirks. Sections of the tree grow and bend over time to create the final result. Being the first version of the algorithm, it is quite rough around the edges, but I hope you will agree that roughness creates a certain unique charm.

metadata.name: Tork #58
metadata.description:
Tork is a generative artwork that invites you into a frenzied, distorted space where order collapses in on itself and clarity slips away.

What started as an exploration into recursive grid subdivision quickly evolved as our good friend Entropy invited itself in and I couldn't resist the temptation to let it take control.

Created to celebrate the 'fxhash turns one' anniversary mint event. #fxhashturnsone

----------

Interaction:

* Press 's' in the Live Mode to save as PNG
* Watch the drawing unfold by adding '&build=1' to the URL in Live Mode
* Change the size by adding '&size=1' to the URL in Live Mode [1=1000, 2=2000, 3=4000, 4=8000]

Features:

* A broad set of colour palettes, subtle and not-so-subtle variations in paint modes, and dramatic layer distortions to discover.
